<div id="rightside">
	<p>3.31.2016 - Live Lattice Boltzmann Fluids</p>
	<p id="indent">So yesterday, I wrote about this website, but today I realized I had some project progress I forgot to talk about. A long time ago, I was doing fluid simulations in a traditional CFD way, where the technique uses partial differential equations to solve for the Navier Stokes Equations of flow.
	</p>
	<p id="indent">So CFD with partial differential equations essentially goes, continuous -> discrete -> sim, but the new technique I've been using is called Lattice Boltzman CFD, and it essentially goes discrete -> continous -> sim. The reason I have veered toward this type of CFD is because it can be accellerated by GPUs. And this allows you to do live interaction with the fluid as it is simulating.
	</p>
	<p id="indent">This is important to me because it increases the tightness of the design loop. I can make changes directly in the environment. Here is an example of me adding wings and bluff bodies to a fluid moving from left-to-right.</p>
	<p>
		<video width="440" controls>
			<source src="videos/livelbmexample.ogv" type='video/ogg; codecs="theora, vorbis"'>
			<source src="videos/livelbmexample.mp4" type='video/mp4; codecs="avc1.42E01E, mp4a.40.2"'>
		</video>
	<small>Simulated using <a href="http://sailfish.us.edu.pl/">Sailfish</a></small>
	</p>

	<p id="indent">Many of our tools require us to partially simulate the tool in our head. Live tools create a different type of interaction where we can become one with the simulation in a state of play. With intermediary steps in the design-and-simulate loop there is a tax that makes it hard to gain intuition.
	</p>
</div>

